Voting rights to be established upon issuance by the Board.\n*   **General Voting:** Class A and Class B shareholders vote together as a single class on most matters. The charter includes an opt-out from class votes that would otherwise be required under Texas law.\n\n### 4. Founder Control & Protective Provisions (Elon Musk)\nThe charter contains specific provisions heavily favoring Class B shareholders and CEO Elon Musk:\n*   **Board Control:** Holders of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, elect **51% of the total number of authorized directors** (rounded up), as long as any Class B shares remain outstanding. \n*   **Director Removal & Vacancies:** Class B directors can only be removed (with or without cause) by a majority vote of Class B shareholders. Vacancies for Class B directors are filled exclusively by Class B shareholders or remaining Class B directors.\n*   **Musk\'s Removal:** Removing Elon Musk from his board or leadership roles (CEO and Chairman) requires the approval of a majority of the voting power of outstanding Class B shares.\n*   **Charter Amendments:** Any charter amendment changing the rights, powers, or preferences of Class B stock requires separate Class B approval.\n*   **Musk\'s Voting Power:** Post-IPO, Musk will beneficially own a majority of the outstanding Class B shares and a majority of the voting power, allowing him to elect all board members and exert significant influence over corporate matters. This will limit the influence of Class A public shareholders.\n*   **Controlled Company Status:** The company will be a "controlled company" under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas rules, exempting it from certain corporate governance requirements.\n\n### 5. Conversion Mechanics & Structural Adjustments\n*   **Class B Conversion:** Each Class B share is convertible into one Class A share at the option of the holder. \n*   **Automatic Conversion:** Class B shares automatically convert to Class A upon transfer, whether or not for value, except for "Permitted Transfers" (e.g., certain inter-family transfers or transfers to permitted entities). This mechanism will gradually increase the relative voting power of remaining Class B holders over time.\n*   **Pre-Offering Reclassifications:** The capital structure gives effect to the "Class C Reclassification" (all Class C shares reclassified into Class A) and the "Preferred Conversion" (all preferred stock converted into Class A and Class B shares) prior to the IPO.\n*   **Stock Splits:** A 10-for-1 stock split occurred in 2022, and a 5-for-1 stock split (for Class A, B, and C) was approved in May 2026.\n*   **Corporate Conversion:** On February 14, 2024, SpaceX converted from a Delaware corporation to a Texas corporation.\n\n### 6. Board Composition\nUpon offering completion, the board will consist of 8 directors:\n*   **Class B Directors (51%):** Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek.\n*   **Common Stock Directors:** Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, and Steve Jurvetson.\n\n### 7. Forward-Looking Financial Targets or Projections\n*   **No specific financial targets or projections** (such as revenue, EBITDA, or future earnings) are disclosed in these chunks.\n*   The text only mentions **estimated net proceeds** from the offering, noting that the actual dollar amounts and share counts are currently blank (represented by placeholders like "$____" or "____ shares"). These will be based on an assumed initial public offering price (the midpoint of the price range on the cover page) after deducting underwriting discounts and expenses.\n*   The company notes it has applied to list its Class A common stock on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas under the symbol **"SPCX"**.',
