pense and Income\n*   **Interest Expense:** For the three months ended March 31, 2026, interest expense increased by $217 million (48.5%) compared to the prior year, primarily due to additional debt raised by the AI segment. Interest expense recognized prior to capitalization was $1,797 million (2025), $1,580 million (2024), and $1,693 million (2023). Cash paid for interest, net of capitalized interest, was $990 million (Q1 2026), $382 million (Q1 2025), $1,476 million (2025), $1,500 million (2024), and $1,365 million (2023).\n*   **Interest Income:** For the three months ended March 31, 2026, interest income increased by $96 million (82.1%) compared to the prior year, driven by increased interest income from cash equivalents and marketable securities. A hypothetical 100 basis point change in market interest rates would have an immaterial effect on interest income.\n*   **Loss on Extinguishment of Debt:** The repayment of the X B-1 Term Loan, X B-3 Term Loan, xAI Fixed Rate Loan, xAI Floating Rate Loan, and xAI 12.5% Senior Secured Notes resulted in a loss on extinguishment of $1,526 million, recorded in Other expense, net.\n\n### 5. Cash Flow Activities\n*   **Investing Activities:** Net cash used in investing activities increased by $5,929 million from 2023 to 2024 (from $4,867 million to $10,796 million), primarily driven by a $6,748 million increase in capital expenditures for data centers, related infrastructure, and space launch facilities, partially offset by a $981 million increase in cash received from marketable securities maturities.\n*   **Financing Activities:**\n    *   **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** Net cash provided by financing activities increased by $6,771 million (from $354 million to $7,125 million), driven by $17,950 million in proceeds from the SpaceX Bridge Loan and other arrangements, and $7,420 million from capital stock sales. This was partially offset by $14,703 million in payments on existing debt/extinguishment costs and $3,838 million in capital stock repurchases following the xAI acquisition.\n    *   **FY 2025 vs. FY 2024:** Net cash provided by financing activities increased by $14,520 million (from $11,830 million to $26,350 million), primarily driven by a $16,055 million increase in proceeds from debt and other financing arrangements for the AI segment.\n\n### 6. Risk Factors and Other Disclosures\n*   **Indebtedness Risks:** The company\'s $29.1 billion indebtedness could materially adversely affect its business by increasing vulnerability to adverse economic conditions, requiring a substantial portion of cash flow for debt payments, limiting flexibility, and exposing the company to variable interest rate risks. It may also adversely affect credit ratings, increase the cost of capital, and limit access to future financing. Failure to comply with debt agreement terms could result in default and accelerated repayment obligations.\n*   **Underwriter Relationships:** Affiliates of several underwriters (Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, BofA Securities, Citigroup, J.P. Morgan, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, RBC Capital Markets, UBS, and Wells Fargo) serve as lenders or administrative agents under the SpaceX Bridge Loan and SpaceX Credit Facility. Morgan Stanley also advised on the xAI acquisition.\n*   **Spectrum Transaction:** Approved by the FCC on May 12, 2026, and expected to close around November 30, 2027. Upon closing, the company intends to use cash on hand or seek alternative financing sources for the amount of EchoStar debt satisfied at or prior to closing.',
