 **4.4 million** X Premium and Premium+ paid subscribers.\n*   **Strategic Vision:** The company intends to evolve X into an “Everything App,” integrating real-time information, communications, media, payments, banking, and more into a single consumer app experience to drive engagement and monetization.\n\n### 4. Advertising Revenue Trends\n*   **Q1 2026:** Advertising revenue was $343 million, a decrease of $100 million from $443 million in Q1 2025. This drop was due to an overhaul of the company’s advertising platform, which impacted ad sales for a short period during the rebuild.\n*   **FY 2025:** Advertising revenue increased by $116 million to $1,844 million (up from $1,728 million in FY 2024) as advertising spend increased from partners on X.\n*   **FY 2024:** Advertising revenue decreased by $595 million to $1,728 million (down from $2,323 million in FY 2023) due to the loss of advertising partners for X.\n*   **Seasonality:** Advertising revenue is highly seasonal, peaking in Q4 due to end-of-year advertiser spending and hitting its lowest point in Q1.\n*   **Strategy:** The company aims to grow advertising revenue per user by making ads feel like content (contextually relevant and integrated into real-time conversations). Grok supports this by helping advertisers with campaign creation, creative optimization, and alignment with trending topics. The company also sees an incremental monetization opportunity by introducing advertising into the stand-alone Grok offering.\n\n### 5. AI Solutions & Infrastructure Revenue Composition\n*   **Composition:** This revenue stream consists of (i) premium subscriptions on X and Grok, (ii) data licensing arrangements, and (iii) API revenue. \n*   **Q1 2026:** Revenue was $475 million, up $191 million from $284 million in Q1 2025. This was driven by a $177 million increase in Grok and X subscription revenue and a $12 million increase in data licensing.\n*   **FY 2025:** Revenue was $1,357 million, up $465 million from $892 